  "prompt": "What is a good substitute for chipotle powder?",
  "response": "If you're out of **chipotle powder** or can't find it, there are several good substitutes that can replicate its smoky, slightly spicy, and earthy flavor profile. Here are some options:\n\n1. **Smoked Paprika + Cayenne Pepper**  \n   - Combine **smoked paprika** for the smokiness and a pinch of **cayenne pepper** for heat. This mix closely mimics chipotle powder's flavor.\n\n2. **Ground Ancho Chili Powder + Smoked Salt**  \n   - Use **ancho chili powder** (made from dried poblano peppers) for mild heat and sweetness, and add a touch of **smoked salt** for smokiness.\n\n3. **Chipotle Chili Flakes**  \n   - If you have **dried chipotle peppers**, grind them into flakes or powder for a direct substitute.\n\n4. **Cumin + Paprika + Cayenne**  \n   - Combine **cumin** for earthiness, **paprika** for mild sweetness, and **cayenne** for heat. Adjust the ratios to taste.\n\n5. **Liquid Smoke + Chili Powder**  \n   - Mix **chili powder** with a few drops of **liquid smoke** to add the smoky element that chipotle powder provides.\n\n6. **Adobo Sauce Powder**  \n   - If you have **canned chipotle peppers in adobo sauce**, you can dry the sauce and grind it into a powder for a very close substitute.\n\n**Tip**: Keep in mind that chipotle powder has a unique balance of smokiness, heat, and sweetness, so you may need to adjust the quantities of your substitute to match the desired flavor.",
